1","about 1165":"about 1165","1207":"1207","Lonsdale, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Levens, Westmorland, England":"Levens, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Yealand Conyers, Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Yealand and Silverdale in Cumberland":"Yealand Redmayne, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Redmayne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Redmain (Cumb). The place, recorded as  <i>Rademan</i> in 1202, is named with Old English  <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + an uncertain second element, perhaps a dialectal form of  <i>man</i> ‘cairn’."],"variants":[{"name":"Redman","meanings":["English: occupational name from Middle English <i>red</i> (Old English <i>hrēod</i>) ‘reed’ + <i>-man</i>, presumably for a thatcher or reed-cutter. Compare   Reeder  .","English: in southeastern England sometimes a topographic name perhaps for someone who lived by a clearing, from Middle English <i>rede</i> (Old English <i>rēod</i>, <i>rȳd</i>) ‘clearing’ + <i>man</i>.","English: habitational name from Redmain (Cumberland), from Old English <i>rēad</i> ‘red’ + an uncertain second element, perhaps a dialect form of <i>man</i> ‘cairn’."]},{"name":"Rothery","meanings":["English: apparently from an Anglicized form of the Welsh or Brittonic personal name <i>Rhydderch</i> (see   Roderick   and   Prothero  )."]},{"name":"Readman","meanings":["1  English:  see  Redmayne  .","2  English:  see  Redman  ."]}]},{"name":"Norman","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, from <i>nord</i> ‘north’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘Norseman’. This name was in use in England before the Conquest, and was reinforced by its use among the Norman invaders themselves. The Normans were the inhabitants of Normandy in northern France, whose name is a reference to the Vikings who took control of the region in the 9th century. In the 11th and 12th centuries they achieved remarkable conquests, including not only Britain but also Sicily, southern Italy, and Antioch. In the Scottish Highlands it is used as the Anglicized equivalent of Tormod ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Norman de Redmayne was born in 1140, in Yorkshire, England, his father, Adam d'Avranches, was 41 and his mother, d'Avranches, was 40. He had at least 2 sons with de Stuteville. He died in 1184, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1140–1184":"1140–1184","1137–1207":"1137–1207","–Female":"Surnud","1165–1225":"1165–1225","1182–Male":"1182–Surnud","1099–1176":"1099–1176","1101–Female":"1101–Surnud","about 1182":"umbes 1182","Aft 1176":"1176","1176":"1176","1099":"1099","1165":"1165","1140":"1140","1184":"1184","1182":"1182","1225":"1225","1137":"1137","1101":"1101","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1207":"1207","Lonsdale, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Levens, Westmorland, England":"Levens, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yealand Conyers, Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yealand and Silverdale in Cumberland":"Yealand Redmayne, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1140–1